{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17518984","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17518984"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T14:08:31+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T14:08:31+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12967"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"12967","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/12967"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.02,0.03,0.07,0.87,0.02]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5405"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"38301"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"5405","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/5405"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12967"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"22770"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"152"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"9123"},{"type":"contributions","id":"9537"},{"type":"contributions","id":"11085"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"38301","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/38301"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 56-year-old woman presents with a three day of pain on urination, increased frequency and urgency. She denies having haematuria and nocturia. Her history includes type 2 diabetes, hypertension, COPD and osteoporosis. Her medications include dapagliflozin, perindopril, salbutamol puffer, denosumab and vitamin D supplements. Her blood pressure is 130/80mmHg, pulse 65/min, temperature 37.0\u003Csup\u003Eo\u003C/sup\u003EC, respiratory rate 14/min and pO\u003Csub\u003E2\u003C/sub\u003E 96% on room air. The physical examination is unremarkable apart from some mild lower abdominal tenderness.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is most likely to have contributed to her current problem?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Vitamin D supplements","Perindopril","Denosumab","Dapagliflozin","Salbutamol"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe patient\u0027s presentation and findings are all suggestive of a urinary tract infection (UTI). As a patient with Type 2 Diabetes Mellitus (T2DM), this patient has an increased risk of UTI due to immune impairments and autonomic neuropathy often associated with T2DM. It is important to analyse the side effect profiles her medications which could predisposes her to UTI. \u003Cstrong\u003EDapagliflozin\u003C/strong\u003E belongs to the class of SGLT2 inhibitors. It acts by reducing the glucose absorption. Adverse drug reactions include euglycemia ketoacidosis and UTI. By reducing glucose reabsorption in the renal proximal tubules, it results in glucosuria and thereby could further predispose her to a UTI. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ENone of the other listed medications are associated with any risk of urinary tract infection. Adverse effects of \u003Cstrong\u003Evitamin D\u003C/strong\u003E include symptoms of hypercalcaemia such as nausea, vomiting, constipation, headache, muscle weakness, polydipsia and polyuria.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPerindopril \u003C/strong\u003Ebelongs to the class of ACE inhibitors, adverse effects include hypotension, dizziness, cough, nausea and renal impairment.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDenosumab\u003C/strong\u003E also known as denosumab is a monoclonal antibody. Adverse effects include eczema, hypercholesterolaemia, MSK pain, hypersensitivity and osteonecrosis of the jaw.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESalbutamol\u003C/strong\u003E is a short acting beta2 agonist. Adverse effects include tremor, palpitation, and headache.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["SGLT2 inhibitors can further predispose diabetic patients to an increased risk of recurrent UTI"],"references":["Petersons CJ. Second steps in managing type 2 diabetes. Australian Prescriber. 2018;41(5):141\u20134. doi:10.18773/austprescr.2018.043","Nitzan O, Elias M, Chazan B, Saliba W. Urinary tract infections in patients with type 2 diabetes mellitus: review of prevalence, diagnosis, and management. Diabetes Metab Syndr Obes. 2015;8:129-136. doi:10.2147/DMSO.S51792"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"22770"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12967"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"22770","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/22770"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2023-07-21T08:49:05+09:30","updatedAt":"2023-07-21T08:49:05+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5405"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"38301"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"152","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/152"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Cystitis","synonyms":["Urinary tract infection","UTI","Lower UTI","Urinary infection","Urinary tract infections"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2021-05-19T22:40:03+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-03-14T14:37:54+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"2"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"contributions","id":"9123","links":{"sel